          "body": "The chapter closes with the second sign at Cana, deliberately paired with the first (2:1-11). A royal official begs Jesus to *come down* to heal his dying son. Jesus rebukes the *signs-and-wonders* mentality (v.48) — and yet, having rebuked it, He grants what was asked, but in a form that *transcends* sign-faith. *Go; your son lives*. The man believes the word *before* any visible confirmation, starts the 20-mile journey home, and discovers his servants meeting him with news that the fever broke at the precise hour Jesus spoke. The chapter that began with Samaritans believing because of His *logos* (v.41) ends with a Gentile-aligned official and his whole household believing because of His *logos* (vv.50, 53). Christ's spoken word is sufficient — across ethnic, social, and physical distance."
